<br>
Code Red was around mid July of 2001.  The fix for Code Red was available mid June of 2001.<br>
<br>
Nimda spread around Sept of 2001.  The fix for Nimda *was* the fix for Code Red which was available mid June of that same year (Nimda was basically a single worm which attempted to exploit several pre-existing flaws to spread--it was effective because it used multiple attack vectors.  The cumlative patch for Code Red would have stopped Nimda in it's tracks.)<br>
<br>
Remember, these are *fixes*.  The disclosure of the exploit is usually a few days before the actual fix is released (disclosure at least to the security community).<br>
<br>
Face it, these so called &quot;hackers&quot; are just not that smart (if they were, don't you think they would be doing something more meaningful).  The VAST majority of what you think of &quot;hackers&quot; are script kiddies.  They take code published in security flaw disclosure documents and copy/paste them to &quot;hack&quot; systems.<br>
<br>
The simple fact of the matter is that the truely talented hacks in this business are people you never hear about.  They often work for security companies spending hours trying to crack systems and once they find a breach, they work directly with the vendors to fix them.  Unfortunately, that sort of thing isn't very glamorous and doesn't make for good Hollywood movies (nor for that matter the evening news).<br>
<br>
