<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i'll still stick to that hack : at least it supports symbolic linking.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Slight correction here, NFS supports mount points.  It's a network file system, the counter part for this on Windows world is DFS.  However, if you mean symlinks on the local file system (such as ext2fs) for mount points, WinXP supports it.  Like I said, drill down to the Disk Management snapin, you'll see what I'm referring to.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>yeah but i am talking XP here. afaik you can't have a unified file tree. you're still going with folders and drives.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
You can.<br>
Mount points, or what NT/XP calls Junction Points (hmmm, wait they may have changed the name before RTMing...) do exactly what you're talking about.  It will provide for a unified file tree.  Do a search on XP help files for junction points and it should take you to what I'm talking about.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>i don't see what C# brings to the table that we need so badly<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
It brings to the table the same things any higher level language does.<br>
<br>
And there's no such thing as a language breeding bad coding, bad coders will code poorly regardless of the language.  I've enough experience in dealing other people's code in at least half a dozen different languages to know at least that much.  One of the nice thing about higher level languages like C# is that you stop worrying about plumbing details and spend more time thinking about design/architecture.  If anything, I would argue that helps improve your coding standard since it allows you the luxury of thinking more about design.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>the .net framework scares the living shit out of me because it looks far more like a contractual trap than an actual solution to a problem. it builds in far too much dependency on MS for my liking.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I think you have a misunderstanding here--not surprising since marketing really fucked up big time with the .Net This and .Net That nonsense.<br>
<br>
.Net Framework is Microsoft's implementation of CLI (Common Language Infrastructure).  The CLI is actually an open standard.  Anyone can create their own implementation of CLI on any platform of their choosing.  That means .Net Framework doesn't lock you into Microsoft.  Do a search on something called Mono.  It's the open source implementation of the CLI.  There are obvious cross platform issues on things like GUI and platform specific APIs, but then that's the case with any cross platform framework.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>but so far i haven't seen anything in recent years that offers any significant benefit over my good old C++ without some kind of significant set of pitfalls.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
The only thing keeping C/C++ around anymore is the fact that there's so many people comfortable using it and reluctant to try something new.  Hell, the productivity increase in using something like C#/Java can't be argued it's just too damn dramatic.<br>
<br>
Is there an overhead in using languages like C#?  Of course.  However, the benefits provided by languages like C# FAR outweighs the ~5 to 20% performance penalty you pay (those are numbers we determined based on internal profiling of our code ported to C# from C++, a port I might add that took one dev about a week and half to do for fairly decent sized project).  I wouldn't recommend writing kernel level modules in C# just yet, but I suspect it won't be long until even that is possible (recall when C++ wasn't suppose to be used for kernel modules because of it's overhead?).<br>
<br>
Be that as it may, if you still perfer C++, by all means stick with C++.  As I said, language is irrelavent. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showMessageRange?topicID=888.topic&start=21&stop=28>2</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showPrevMessage?topicID=888.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showNextMessage?topicID=888.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=888.topic&index=20><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/addReply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.emailToFriend?topicID=888.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.threadControl?topicID=888.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/softsky/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=888.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=888.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/unsubscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to stop receiving email notification of replies"> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies</a> <br> </td